Japan, while originally the leader in cellphones has forfeited its lead and has been outcompeted by Finnish and American cellphones, with surprisingly low [smartphone adoption](http://www.wired.com/beyond_the_beyond/2011/12/42-major-countries-ranked-by-smartphone-penetration-rates/) c. 2011, perhaps related to the continued [use of fax machines](https://www.nytimes.com/2013/02/14/world/asia/in-japan-the-fax-machine-is-anything-but-a-relic.html?pagewanted=all "In High-Tech Japan, the Fax Machines Roll On") (whose Japanese popularity peaked at around [60% of households 2007-2012](http://www.washingtonpost.com/world/asia_pacific/in-japan-fax-machines-find-a-final-place-to-thrive/2012/06/07/gJQAshFPMV_print.html "In Japan, fax machines remain important because of language and culture")); Gibson's article seems laughably out of date in this [age](http://www.washingtonpost.com/world/as-apple-and-samsung-dominate-japans-tech-giants-are-in-a-free-fall/2012/09/28/04c6eb36-0944-11e2-afff-d6c7f20a83bf_story.html "As Apple and Samsung dominate, Japan's tech giants are in a free fall") [of the iPhone](http://globalvoicesonline.org/2011/10/18/japan-were-losing-to-apple-and-heres-why/) ([part 2](http://globalvoicesonline.org/2011/11/05/japans-it-exodus-a-personal-perspective-part-2/print/)), but it *was* true! One could also wonder why Internet cafes are [an institution](!Wikipedia "PC bang") in South Korea and an obscure niche [in Japan](http://www.japaninc.com/article.php?articleID=136)? ([Patrick McKenzie](http://www.kalzumeus.com/2011/12/01/inaugural-kalzumeus-podcast-japan-startups-ab-testing-and-more/) makes multiple interesting remarks on the parlous state of Japanese IT and cellphones which are too lengthy to quote here.)

Another curious case is the Japanese robotics industry - their [walking robots and competitions](/docs/eva/2005-murakami#robots) have been presented triumphantly as the culmination of Japanese technological development, but the odd thing is, the R&D programs that produced [ASIMO](!Wikipedia) or [HRP-4C](!Wikipedia) are already looking quixotic and ill-fated, re-runs of the [Fifth Generation project](!Wikipedia "Fifth generation computer"). [Industrial robots](!Wikipedia) were a very successful field for Japan, but that was decades ago. What robots has Japan produced that were as useful as a Roomba? Why were the robots at the Fukushima plant [*American*](http://www.guardian.co.uk/world/2011/mar/29/japan-nuclear-plant-us-robots "Japan nuclear plant gets help from US robots: Obama administration sends shipment of robots to help regain control over stricken Fukushima nuclear plant")? (And then there is the exploding field of aerial drones and swarms, which Japan seems excluded from. One thinks of Edsger W. Dijkstra - "The question of whether Machines Can Think... is about as relevant as the question of whether Submarines Can Swim." Or walk, as the case may be.)

Japanese Internet services restrict themselves to Japan either by apathy or by actively blocking foreign IP address via [geoip](!Wikipedia), which may ultimately be a recipe for failure. (The South Korean social network [Cyworld](!Wikipedia) failed in its attempts to expand internationally, and now its [lunch is](http://www.koreatimes.co.kr/www/news/opinon/2011/02/137_81147.html) [being eaten](http://metropolitician.blogs.com/scribblings_of_the_metrop/2011/04/the-absence-of-a-korean-google-and-the-failure-of-the-korean-intranet.html) [by](http://metropolitician.blogs.com/scribblings_of_the_metrop/2010/06/facebook-taking-over-korea-as-predicted.html) [Facebook](https://web.archive.org/web/20140731220709/http://seoulspace.co.kr/blog/2012/05/23/cyworld-losing-to-facebook/). YouTube has done a similar number on Korean competitors. The Japanese equivalent to Cyworld, [Mixi](!Wikipedia) seemed to be [fending off Facebook](http://articles.sfgate.com/2011-02-08/business/27107322_1_executive-officer-mark-zuckerberg-mixi-social-networking), at least until [mid-2012](http://www.digitalintheround.com/japan-mixi-facebook/ "Mixi in Japan: the rise, the fall and the Facebook takeover") or so.) Another example comes from P2P filesharing, which is rarely done for [movies](http://latimesblogs.latimes.com/the_big_picture/2010/05/who-do-korean-moviegoers-get-to-see-iron-man-2-way-ahead-of-japan-.html) or [music](http://thegrandnarrative.com/2013/07/01/japan-illegal-music-downloads/) (in favor of [growing CD sales](http://blogs.wsj.com/japanrealtime/2013/06/24/as-cds-spin-on-in-japan-tower-records-rocks-on/); ["many top [K-pop] artists make more money from one week in Japan than they do in one year in Korea"](http://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-asia-pacific-13760064 "The dark side of South Korean pop music")); this is not due just to a sclerotic entertainment industry as we note a similar obsession with CDs in amateur doujin circles as well. Curiously, Japanese geeks who *do* fileshare choose to use [Winny](!Wikipedia)/[Share](!Wikipedia "Share (P2P)")/[Perfect Dark](!Wikipedia "Perfect Dark (P2P)") - all of which are closed-source, employ [security through obscurity](!Wikipedia), Windows-only, implementation-defined, are not used outside Japan, and are known to be insecure with multiple arrests & NetAgent claims to have broken Perfect Dark; from the perspective of Western users, these are all fatal objections and they haven't used such insecure and untrustworthy P2P software since the days of Napster and Kazaa. Even Western [hentai](!Wikipedia) [porn sites](http://2dteleidoscope.wordpress.com/2011/09/18/tag-porn-culture-of-categorization/) have better implementations and contents than the Japanese sites, though it's the Japanese who produce all their content!

[W. David Marx](http://neomarxisme.com/biography.html) in 2009 listed other striking aspects of the Japanese intranet, as it were, in his essay ["The Fear... of the Internet"](http://neojaponisme.com/2009/05/19/the-fear-of-the-internet/); from just one section, 'User Trepidation':

> - A total and comprehensive refusal of Japanese social network site users to post real pictures of themselves (and often, real names)
> - An obsession with ultra-long and complicated mobile-email addresses as a spam prevention measure, despite the fact that its effect may be minimal, especially when weighed against the inconvenience.
> - A lack of user generated media - YouTube clips, in particular - featuring Japanese faces and real names. Many performers, despite virtuoso-level skills, wear masks or otherwise obscure faces in their video content. [eg. the entirely masked [Nico Nico Orchestra](http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=F1KgDz_An2s)]
> - The predominance of anonymous sites like [2ch](!Wikipedia) as the main corridors of internet culture.
> - Blog writers, who have not established fame through other media, almost never reveal real names, even when the information and service provided is of professional quality and not explicitly personal. (More on this [here](http://neomarxisme.com/wdmwordpress/?p=129).)
> - The local discomfort towards Google Street Maps - debated on somewhat cultural-essentialist grounds - vastly outweighed the benefits for the louder section of Japanese users, forcing Google to plan a re-shoot of all the streets with a 'lower angle camera'.

I was struck by the point that "Newspapers do not offer full content online and quickly erase content lest it become searchable archives." inasmuch as during my [_Evangelion_ research](otaku), I had been using an interview published by _[Mainichi Shimbun](!Wikipedia)_ online, but the entire site vanished months later in a merger with [Microsoft Japan](!Wikipedia); I assumed it would still be available in the [Internet Archive](!Wikipedia), except the IA had blocked access to every single page ever in the entire domain. More extraordinarily, this was not accomplished via the usual [robots.txt](!Wikipedia) mechanism, implying _Mainichi Shimbun_ had privately contacted the IA to ask for a custom block on the domain!

